In looking back at his tenure, Mr. Thompson said he was proud of diversifying the pensions’ portfolios into a large number of private equity funds and other investment vehicles. He said this had reduced exposure to market risk and helped weather the turmoil on Wall Street in 2008.But the push into new investments also allowed Mr. Thompson to forge new relationships with fund managers, and the often politically connected placement agents they hired to help gain access to pension officials.Nowhere was Mr. Thompson’s embrace of those investment firms more evident than on the guest list to his second swearing-in, in January 2006. The 250 names included a small number of relatives, union leaders and elected officials; more than 50 lobbyists; and another 50 fund managers, placement agents and others who stood to gain from the city’s pension funds.Mr. Maitland was one.The comptroller’s office had not previously invested in convertible bonds, which generally have lower yields but higher fees than ordinary corporate bonds. Mr. Thompson’s move into convertibles in 2008, when Mr. Maitland has said few pensions had an appetite for them, gave Advent a huge new client: Mr. Thompson invested $374 million, and his successor, Comptroller John C. Liu, invested an additional $292 million. Today, the funds’ $855 million — the investments have done well, growing on average by just over 8 percent — represents more than 10 percent of Advent’s assets under management.Mr. Thompson made no apologies for investing with Mr. Maitland, calling him “probably one of the two best in the world” in convertibles and adding, “He’s done well for the city.”He said Mr. Maitland was “an acquaintance” and had not raised money for him this year. He said Mr. Maitland was not involved in his wife’s talks with the A.S.P.C.A.‘Open Door’ PolicyMr. Maitland, in an interview, said he could not recall details of the fund-raiser he held for Mr. Thompson in 2001, and cautioned against drawing any link between that and Mr. Thompson’s first investments with Advent, seven years later. “If we were counting on that, we’d be out of business,” he said.
Photo






Mr. Thompson announcing his re-election bid for comptroller in 2005.

Credit
            Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times        


But Mr. Maitland said a mutually beneficial relationship was not necessarily bad. “We’ve done well by the city and the city’s done well by us,” he said. “That’s how it’s supposed to work.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Friends say Mr. Maitland made calls seeking support for Mr. Thompson’s current mayoral bid, but Mr. Maitland played down any role. “If someone asks me, do I think he’s a good guy, do I think he’s competent, I say yes,” he said. But he added, “I’m not supporting any one person.”Other donors who were invited to the swearing-in ceremony gained from pension business:■ Richard C. Dresdale, president of Fenway Partners, and its lawyer, Josh Leuchtenburg. In May 2004, Mr. Dresdale donated $2,500 to Mr. Thompson’s campaign; that October, he and Fenway’s chairman met with Mr. Thompson in his offices. In December, Mr. Thompson attended a breakfast set up by Kasirer Consulting, his political fund-raising firm, with Mr. Dresdale and Mr. Leuchtenburg. Over the next two weeks, they and others at Fenway gave over $10,000 to Mr. Thompson. Fenway Partners began receiving city pension fund business in late 2007.■ Julio Ramirez Jr., a placement agent at Wetherly Capital. He met with Mr. Thompson in January 2005 and gave his campaign $4,000 five days later. Wetherly earned placement fees that year on $40 million in pension investments made by Mr. Thompson’s office. (Mr. Ramirez later pleaded guilty to paying kickbacks to get contracts from the state pension fund.)■ Alfred R. Villalobos, a former Los Angeles deputy mayor. He and his daughter gave Mr. Thompson $6,950 in 2004; Mr. Villalobos met with Mr. Thompson three times later that year. His firm received fees on $270 million in new investments by the New York City pension funds in 2007. (Mr. Villalobos was later charged with forging documents in connection with a $3 billion investment by the California state pension system.)■ Jerry Weiss, an Albany lobbyist, and Gary Furhman, a fund manager who used him as a placement agent. Mr. Weiss and employees at Mr. Furhman’s company, GF Capital, donated a combined $12,900 to Mr. Thompson’s campaign in 2004. In May 2005, the Kasirer firm arranged a meeting for Mr. Fuhrman with Mr. Thompson and the pension funds’ chief investment officer. That fall, Mr. Thompson met with Mr. Fuhrman and Mr. Weiss in the comptroller’s board room. In May 2006, Mr. Weiss donated an additional $4,950. GF Capital won a total of $48 million in investments from four city pension funds in 2006.Mr. Weiss, it turns out, did not have the required securities license. In a 2010 settlement with Andrew M. Cuomo, then the attorney general and now the governor, he agreed to repay $78,000 in fees he got from GF Capital for lining up the city’s investments.Asked about his meetings with donors who won pension business, Mr. Thompson said he had an “open door” policy but emphasized that “any investment that was done went through multiple hurdles.”

The practice of investment firms and their placement agents flooding public pension overseers with political contributions attracted the attention of federal and state prosecutors and the Securities and Exchange Commission after a series of so-called pay-to-play scandals in recent years. Mr. Hevesi went to prison after admitting that he had accepted about $1 million from a California businessman to whom he awarded some $250 million in state pension fund business.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Thompson said he pushed for reforms to the process, too, including a ban on the involvement of placement agents with city pension funds. That took effect in 2009, eight months before he left office.
